{"title_page": "Gedhun Choekyi Nyima", "text_new": "{{short description|Tibetan religious leader, recognized as the 11th Panchen Lama by the 14th Dalai Lama}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gedhun Choekyi Nyima\n| title              = 11th [[Panchen Lama]]<br /><small>according to the 14th Dalai Lama</small>\n| image              = The_11th_Panchen_Lama_Gedun_Choekyi_Nyima.jpg\n| caption            = Gedhun Choekyi Nyima<br />The 11th Panchen Lama in 1995\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1989|4|25}}\n| death_date         = \n| module             = {{Infobox royalty|embed=yes\n|succession = [[Panchen Lama]]\n|reign = 14 May 1995 \u2013 present\n|predecessor = [[Choekyi Gyaltsen]]}}\n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|1995|05|17|1989|04|25|df=y}}\n| disappeared_place  = [[Lhari County]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1995|05|17}}\n}}\n\n'''Gedhun Choekyi Nyima''' (born on April 25, 1989, in [[Lhari County]], [[Tibet]]<ref>[https://www.uscirf.gov/gedhun-choekyi-nyima-the-panchen-lama Gedhun Choekyi Nyima \u2013 The Panchen Lama], United States Commission on International Religious Freedom</ref>) is the 11th [[Panchen Lama]] of [[Tibetan Buddhism]] according to the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]]. He was declared the 11th [[Panchen Lama]] by the 14th Dalai Lama on 14 May 1995. He was rejected by the search team appointed by the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.dw.com/zh/%E5%8D%81%E5%B9%B4%E4%BA%86%E8%BE%BE%E8%B5%96%E6%8C%87%E5%AE%9A%E7%9A%84%E7%8F%AD%E7%A6%85%E4%BB%8A%E5%AE%89%E5%9C%A8/a-1584571?&zhongwen=simp | title = \u5341\u5e74\u4e86\uff1a\u8fbe\u8d56\u6307\u5b9a\u7684\u73ed\u7985\u4eca\u5b89\u5728 | quote = \u751f\u94a6\u00b7\u6d1b\u6851\u575a\u8d5e\u8bf4\uff1a\u201c\u8fbe\u8d56\u64c5\u81ea\u5ba3\u5e03\u7684\u2018\u8f6c\u4e16\u7075\u7ae5\u2019\u4e0d\u5177\u5907\u4efb\u4f55\u5165\u74f6\u63a3\u7b7e\u7684\u6761\u4ef6\u3002\u6211\u4eec\u624e\u4ec0\u4f26\u5e03\u5bfa\u6c11\u4e3b\u7ba1\u7406\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a\u73ed\u7985\u8f6c\u4e16\u7075\u7ae5\u5bfb\u8bbf\u5c0f\u7ec4\u548c\u5e7f\u5927\u50e7\u4f17\u575a\u51b3\u4e0d\u540c\u610f\u628a\u4ed6\u4f5c\u4e3a\u5165\u74f6\u63a3\u7b7e\u5019\u9009\u7075\u7ae5\u3002\u201d}}</ref> He was born in [[Lhari County]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]. After his selection, he was taken into what the PRC government described as protective custody<ref name=\"buddhistchannel.tv\">[http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=70,4013,0,0,1,0 Gedhun Choekyi Nyima the XIth Panchen Lama turns 18: Still disappeared] The Buddhist Channel, 25 April 2007</ref><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4551425.stm |work = BBC News |title = Tibet's missing spiritual guide |date = 16 May 2005 |accessdate = 3 May 2010}}</ref> and has not been acknowledged in public since 17 May 1995.<ref name=\"buddhistchannel.tv\" /><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\" />\n\n== Selection of the 11th Panchen Lama ==\n{{Tibetan-Chinese-box\n|t = \u0f51\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f51\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f49\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\n|w = dge 'dun chos kyi nyi ma\n|ipa = {{IPA-bo|\u0261end\u1ef9 t\u0255\u02b0\u00f8ci \u0272ima}}\n|z = G\u00ead\u00fcn Qoigyi Nyima\n|ts = Gend\u00fcn Ch\u00f6kyi Nyima\n|e = Gedhun Choekyi Nyima\n|tc = \u66f4\u767b\u78ba\u5409\u5c3c\u746a\n|s = \u66f4\u767b\u786e\u5409\u5c3c\u739b\n|p = G\u00e8ngd\u0113ng Qu\u00e8j\u00ed N\u00edm\u01ce\n}}\n{{Tibetan Buddhism}}\n\nFour days before his death, the 10th [[Panchen Lama]] made his own will publicly to follow the tradition. On 24 January, following the opening ceremony of the Ling Pagoda, with religious figures in Tibet, Qinghai, Gansu, Sichuan and Yunnan provinces and autonomous regions, the 10th Penchen Lama held a special talk on the reincarnation of the Living Buddha, proposing that \"the three candidate boys should be identified first and then investigated one by one\" and \"I would like to take the lead by drawing lots of [[Golden Urn]] before the image of Sakyamuni.\" <ref>{{cite news | url = http://blog.wenxuecity.com/blog/frontend.php?act=articlePrint&blogId=29089&date=200711&postId=13943 | title = \u73ed\u7985\u8f6c\u4e16\u7eaa\u5b9e | quote = \u7b2c\u5341\u4e16\u73ed\u7985\u5927\u5e08\u5706\u5bc2\u524d\u56db\u5929\uff0c\u53731\u670824\u65e5\uff0c\u5728\u4e3b\u6301\u7075\u5854\u5f00\u5149\u5178\u793c\u540e\u7684\u897f\u85cf\u3001\u9752\u6d77\u3001\u7518\u8083\u3001\u56db\u5ddd\u3001\u4e91\u5357\u4e94\u7701\u533a\u90e8\u5206\u5b97\u6559\u754c\u4eba\u58eb\u5ea7\u8c08\u4f1a\u4e0a\uff0c\u7279\u522b\u8c08\u4e86\u6d3b\u4f5b\u8f6c\u4e16\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u63d0\u51fa\u5e94\u201c\u5148\u627e\u51fa\u4e09\u4e2a\u5019\u9009\u7075\u7ae5\uff0c\u7136\u540e\u9010\u4e00\u8fdb\u884c\u8c03\u67e5\u201d\uff0c\u201c\u6211\u60f3\u5728\u91ca\u8fe6\u725f\u5c3c\u50cf\u524d\uff0c\u91c7\u53d6\u2018\u91d1\u74f6\u63a3\u7b7e\u2019\u7684\u529e\u6cd5\u6765\u786e\u5b9a\u3002\u201d\u8fd9\u4e9b\u8bdd\uff0c\u662f\u5927\u5e08\u4e34\u7ec8\u524d\u7684\u9057\u613f\u3002}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of the [[10th Panchen Lama]] in 1989, the search for an individual to be recognised as his reincarnation by Tibetan Buddhists quickly became mired in mystery and controversy, as Tibet had been under the [[Annexation of Tibet|occupation and control]] of the anti-religious [[government of the People's Republic of China]] since 1959.<ref>[http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html Gedhun Choekyi Nyima: the XIth Panchen Lama of Tibet] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324212758/http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThree days after the death of the 10th Panchen Lama, the Premier of the State Council published its decision on how the 11th Panchen Lama was to be selected, claiming to have taken advice from the committee of [[Tashi Lhunpo Monastery]] and monks.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://zh.wikisource.org/zh-hans/%E5%9B%BD%E5%8A%A1%E9%99%A2%E5%85%B3%E4%BA%8E%E7%AC%AC%E5%8D%81%E4%B8%96%E7%8F%AD%E7%A6%85%E5%A4%A7%E5%B8%88%E6%B2%BB%E4%B8%A7%E5%92%8C%E8%BD%AC%E4%B8%96%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98%E7%9A%84%E5%86%B3%E5%AE%9A | title = \u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u5173\u4e8e\u7b2c\u5341\u4e16\u73ed\u7985\u5927\u5e08\u6cbb\u4e27\u548c\u8f6c\u4e16\u95ee\u9898\u7684\u51b3\u5b9a}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.sohu.com/20050412/n225154033.shtml |title = \u7b2c\u5341\u4e16\u73ed\u7985\u5927\u5e08\u7684\u5706\u5bc2\u548c\u9057\u8a00}}</ref>\n\nArmed with Beijing's approval, the head of the Panchen Lama search committee, Chadrel [[Rinpoche]], maintained private communication with the Dalai Lama in order to arrive at a mutually acceptable candidate for both the Dalai Lama and Beijing authorities concerning the Panchen Lama's reincarnation.<ref>[http://www.tchrd.org/press/2001/pr20010824.html TCHRD: Chadrel Rinpoche's fate unknown] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602174257/http://www.tchrd.org/press/2001/pr20010824.html |date=2 June 2008 }}</ref> After the [[Tenzin Gyatso, 14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] named Gedhun Choekyi Nyima as the 11th incarnation of the Panchen Lama on 14 May 1995, Chinese authorities had Chadrel Rinpoche arrested and charged with [[treason]]. According to the Tibetan Government in Exile, he was replaced by Sengchen Lobsang Gyaltsen, so chosen because he was more likely to agree with the [[Communist Party of China|party line]].<ref>[http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov11.html Update-Communist China set to decide on a rival Panchen Lama] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725045825/http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov11.html |date=25 July 2008 }}</ref> Sengchen had been a political opponent of both the [[Tenzin Gyatso, 14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] and the [[10th Panchen Lama]].<ref>[http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov10b.html Communist China set to decide on a rival Panchen Lama] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324003948/http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov10b.html |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref>  Because of the history of rivalry between different sects of Tibetan Buddhism, many Tibetans and scholars believe that this was a tactical move by the [[Chinese Communist Party]] (CCP) to create more unrest and disunity between the typically unified Tibetan peoples.<ref>{{cite web|last=Coonan |first=Clifford |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-appoints-panchen-lama-in-tactical-move-to-quell-unrest-1914309.html |title=China appoints Panchen Lama in tactical move to quell unrest - Asia - World |publisher=The Independent |date=2010-03-02 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://weblog.savetibet.org/2011/08/24/propaganda-and-the-panchen-lama-playing-politics/ |title=Propaganda and the Panchen Lama: playing politics |publisher=Weblog.savetibet.org |date=2011-08-25 |accessdate=2013-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308133516/http://weblog.savetibet.org/2011/08/24/propaganda-and-the-panchen-lama-playing-politics/ |archivedate=8 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe new search committee ignored the Dalai Lama's 14 May announcement and instead chose from a list of finalists which excluded Gedhun Choekyi Nyima. In selecting a name, lottery numbers were drawn from a [[Golden Urn]], a procedure used in Tibet by the Chinese (Manchu) emperor in 1793.<ref>Alex McKay, ''The History of Tibet : The Modern Period'', Routledge 2003, {{ISBN|0-415-30844-5}}, p. 32. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3BPsOQe654IC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA32#v=onepage Google books]</ref> The 14th Dalai Lama stated that the Tibetan method involves using possessions of the former Lama to identify his reincarnation, as the new child incarnate will reportedly recognize his past items amid miscellaneous ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dalailama.com/biography/reincarnation |title=Reincarnation &#124; The Office of His Holiness The Dalai Lama |publisher=Dalailama.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref> On January 26, 1940, the Regent Reting Rinpoche requested the Central Government to exempt Tenzin Gyatso from the lot-drawing process of the [[Golden Urn]] to become the 14th Dalai Lama.<ref name=\"Goldstein1991\">{{cite book|author=Melvyn C. Goldstein|title=A History of Modern Tibet, 1913-1951: The Demise of the Lamaist State|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Upwq0I-wm7YC&pg=PA328|date=18 June 1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-91176-5|pages=328 ff.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livingbuddha.us.com/view-d59c6c9eba6e4beb842b893f40fdec75.html|title=Report to Wu Zhongxin from the Regent Reting Rinpoche Regarding the Process of Searching and Recognizing the Thirteenth Dalai lama's Reincarnated Soul Boy as well as the Request for an Exemption to Drawing Lots - - The Reincarnation of Living Buddhas|website=www.livingbuddha.us.com}}</ref> The request was approved by the Central Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livingbuddha.us.com/view-54a211e996dd4f9fa9671e9489317a42.html|title=The National Government's Decree on the Special Approval of Recognizing Lhamo Thondup as the Fourteenth Dalai Lama with an Exemption of Drawing Lots and the Appropriation of the Expenditure for His Enthronement - - The Reincarnation of Living Buddhas|website=www.livingbuddha.us.com}}</ref> Chinese authorities announced [[Gyancain Norbu]] as the search committee's choice on 11 November 1995.<ref>Isabel Hilton, A Reporter at Large, \"Spies in the House of Faith,\" The New Yorker, 23 August 1999, p. 170</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] reported that the CCP's choice of [[Gyancain Norbu]] was rejected by most Tibetans.<ref>{{Cite news |title = Tibet's missing spiritual guide |work = BBC |accessdate = 15 November 2010 |date = 16 May 2005 |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4551425.stm}}</ref> Alexander Norman wrote, \"Today, the Panchen Lamas are famous for having two claimants to the [[wikt:see#Noun|see]] of [[Tashi Lhunpo Monastery|Tashilhunpo]]: one recognised by the present [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] and taken into [[house arrest]] by the Chinese, the other recognised by China but by no one else.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Norman|first1=Alexander|title=Holder of the White Lotus: The Lives of the Dalai Lama|date=2008|publisher=Little, Brown|location=London|isbn=978-0-316-85988-2|page=165}}</ref>\n\n== Whereabouts ==\nSince his selection, the whereabouts of Gedhun Choekyi Nyima have been unknown.<ref>{{cite web |last=Coonan |first=Clifford |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-appoints-panchen-lama-in-tactical-move-to-quell-unrest-1914309.html |title=China appoints Panchen Lama in tactical move to quell unrest - Asia - World |publisher=The Independent |date=2010-03-02 |accessdate=2013-12-25}}</ref> Officials state that his whereabouts are kept undisclosed to protect him.<ref>[http://www.xizang-zhiye.org/gb/xzxinwen/0504/index.html Xizang-zhiye 27 April 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824025010/http://www.xizang-zhiye.org/gb/xzxinwen/0504/index.html|date=24 August 2006}}</ref> [[Human Rights|Human rights]] organizations termed him the \"youngest [[political prisoner]] in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/23/AR2006042301349.html |title=World's youngest political prisoner turns 17 |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=2006-04-23 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref><ref>Laird, Thomas (2006). ''The Story of Tibet: Conversations with the Dalai Lama'', p 374. Grove Press, N.Y. {{ISBN|978-0-8021-1827-1}}.</ref> No foreign party has been allowed to visit him.<ref name=\"KumarTestimony\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/publications/download/testimony-of-mr-t-kumar-us-china-relations|title=Amnesty International Testimony US \u2013 China Relations before the Committee on Foreign Relations United States Senate by T. Kumar, Advocacy Director for Asia|date=11 September 2003|publisher=US Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Committee on the Rights of the Child]] requested to be told of Nyima's whereabouts on 28 May 1996. ''[[Xinhua]]'' declined, responding that Nyima was at risk of being \"kidnapped by separatists\" and that \"his security had been threatened\".<ref>[http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html Site of the TCHRD] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324212758/http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref> The Committee requested a visit with Gedhun Choekyi Nyima, supported by a campaign of more than 400 celebrities and associations petitioning for the visit, including six [[Nobel Prize]] winners.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.tibet.fr/old/panchen_appel.htm |title=Appel Pour Le Plus Jeune Prisonnier Politique Du Monde |publisher=Tibet.fr |date=1995-05-14 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref><ref name=\"UNPO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unpo.org/content/view/3948/84/ |title=UNPO \u2013 WS on Panchen Lamas Case |publisher=Unpo.org |date=2006-03-09 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref> According to statements by the Chinese government from 1998, he was then leading a normal life.<ref name=\"KumarTestimony\" />\n\nIn May 2007, [[Asma Jahangir]], Special Rapporteur on Freedom of Religion or Belief of the [[UN Human Rights Council]], asked the Chinese authorities what measures they had taken to implement the recommendation of the Committee on the Rights of the Child, that the government should allow an independent expert to visit and confirm the well-being of Gedhun Choekyi Nyima while respecting his right to privacy, and that of his parents. In a response dated 17 July 2007, the Chinese authorities said: \"Gedhun Choekyi Nyima is a perfectly ordinary Tibetan boy, in an excellent state of health, leading a normal, happy life and receiving a good education and cultural upbringing. He is currently in upper secondary school, he measures {{cvt|165|cm|ftin|disp=sqbr}} in height and is easy-going by nature. He studies hard and his school results are very good. He likes Chinese traditional culture and has recently taken up calligraphy. His parents are both State employees, and his brothers and sisters are either already working or at university. The allegation that he disappeared together with his parents and that his whereabouts remain unknown is simply not true.\" This response did not answer the question about a visit or confirmation.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.phayul.com/news/article.aspx?id=20897&article=China+Fails+to+Respond+to+UN+Rights+Expert's+Question+on+Panchen+Lama&t=1&c=1 |title=China Fails to Respond to UN Rights Expert's Question on Panchen Lama |date=25 April 2008 |accessdate=28 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, on the twentieth anniversary of Gendun Choekyi Nyima's disappearance, Chinese officials announced \"The reincarnated child Panchen Lama you mentioned is being educated, living a normal life, growing up healthily and does not wish to be disturbed.\"<ref>{{cite web |title = China says Panchen Lama 'living a normal life' 20 years after disappearance |url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/06/china-says-panchen-lama-living-a-normal-life-20-years-after-disappearance |publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=September 6, 2015 |accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the [[Dalai Lama]] declared that he knew from a \"reliable source\" that the Panchen Lama he had recognized, Gedhun Choekyi Nyima, was alive and receiving normal education. He said he hoped that the PRC appointed Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.<ref>[https://www.thestatesman.com/india/11th-panchen-lama-alive-receiving-education-dalai-lama-1502627372.html 11th Panchen Lama alive, receiving education: Dalai Lama], ''The Statesman'', April 25, 2018: \"Tibetan spiritual leader Dalai Lama on Wednesday said 11th Panchen Lama Gedhun Choekyi Nyima \u201caccording to reliable source is alive and receiving normal education\u201d. Talking to the media at Gaggal Airport in Kangra district after returning from four-day Delhi visit, Lama hoped that the official Panchen Lama studies well under the guidance of a good teacher. \u201cThen the Panchen Lama, which I recognised sometime back, there was no news, but then according to reliable information, he is still alive and receiving normal education. So we will see,\u201d he said. He said there are instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, \u201cwhere a reincarnated lama took more than one manifestation\u201d.\"</ref><ref>Dr. Andrea Galli, [https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2018/05/09/dalai-lama-and-the-panchen-lama-quarrel-the-way-for-rapprochement-with-china/ Dalai Lama and the Panchen Lama quarrel: The way for rapprochement with China], ''Modern Diplomacy'', May 9, 2018.</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Gedhun Choekyi Nyima [[Forced disappearance|has not been seen by any independent observer since his disappearance]] in 1995.<ref>[http://www.tibetanreview.net/dalai-lama-cites-reliable-source-as-saying-panchen-lama-alive-speaks-well-for-the-chinese-appointed-counter/ Dalai Lama cites \u2018reliable source\u2019 as saying Panchen Lama alive, speaks well for the Chinese appointed counter], ''[[Tibetan Review]]'', April 27, 2018  : \"Following the passing away of the 10th Panchen Lama Choekyi Gyaltsen in Jan 1989, Tibet\u2019s exiled spiritual leader formally proclaimed six-year-old Gedhun Choekyi Nyima born in Tibet as his undisputed reincarnation on May 14, 1995. Three days later, the Chinese government took him and his family away to be never seen or heard from again.\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: post-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4551425.stm BBC News article \u2013 \"Tibet's missing spiritual guide\"]\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Panchen Lama]]|1989|April 25}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Choekyi Gyaltsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Panchen Lama|Reincarnation of the Panchen Lama]]<br /><small>([[Government of Tibet in Exile]] interpretation)|years=1995\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Panchen Lamas |state = uncollapsed }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nyima, Gedhun Choekyi}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:Forced disappearances in China]]\n[[Category:Panchen Lamas|Panchen Lama XI]]\n[[Category:People from Nagqu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tibetan religious leader, recognized as the 11th Panchen Lama by the 14th Dalai Lama}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gedhun Choekyi Nyima\n| title              = 11th [[Panchen Lama]]<br /><small>according to the 14th Dalai Lama</small>\n| image              = The_11th_Panchen_Lama_Gedun_Choekyi_Nyima.jpg\n| caption            = Gedhun Choekyi Nyima<br />The 11th Panchen Lama in 1995\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1989|4|25}}\n| death_date         = \n| module             = {{Infobox royalty|embed=yes\n|succession = [[Panchen Lama]]\n|reign = 14 May 1995 \u2013 present\n|predecessor = [[Choekyi Gyaltsen]]}}\n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|1995|05|17|1989|04|25|df=y}}\n| disappeared_place  = [[Lhari County]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]\n| disappeared_status = {{Missing for|1995|05|17}}\n}}\n\n'''Gedhun Choekyi Nyima''' (born on April 25, 1989, in [[Lhari County]], [[Tibet]]<ref>[https://www.uscirf.gov/gedhun-choekyi-nyima-the-panchen-lama Gedhun Choekyi Nyima \u2013 The Panchen Lama], United States Commission on International Religious Freedom</ref>) is the 11th [[Panchen Lama]] of [[Tibetan Buddhism]] according to the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]]. He was declared the 11th [[Panchen Lama]] by the 14th Dalai Lama on 14 May 1995. He was rejected by the search team appointed by the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.dw.com/zh/%E5%8D%81%E5%B9%B4%E4%BA%86%E8%BE%BE%E8%B5%96%E6%8C%87%E5%AE%9A%E7%9A%84%E7%8F%AD%E7%A6%85%E4%BB%8A%E5%AE%89%E5%9C%A8/a-1584571?&zhongwen=simp | title = \u5341\u5e74\u4e86\uff1a\u8fbe\u8d56\u6307\u5b9a\u7684\u73ed\u7985\u4eca\u5b89\u5728 | quote = \u751f\u94a6\u00b7\u6d1b\u6851\u575a\u8d5e\u8bf4\uff1a\u201c\u8fbe\u8d56\u64c5\u81ea\u5ba3\u5e03\u7684\u2018\u8f6c\u4e16\u7075\u7ae5\u2019\u4e0d\u5177\u5907\u4efb\u4f55\u5165\u74f6\u63a3\u7b7e\u7684\u6761\u4ef6\u3002\u6211\u4eec\u624e\u4ec0\u4f26\u5e03\u5bfa\u6c11\u4e3b\u7ba1\u7406\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a\u73ed\u7985\u8f6c\u4e16\u7075\u7ae5\u5bfb\u8bbf\u5c0f\u7ec4\u548c\u5e7f\u5927\u50e7\u4f17\u575a\u51b3\u4e0d\u540c\u610f\u628a\u4ed6\u4f5c\u4e3a\u5165\u74f6\u63a3\u7b7e\u5019\u9009\u7075\u7ae5\u3002\u201d}}</ref> He was born in [[Lhari County]], [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]. After his selection, he was taken into what the PRC government described as protective custody<ref name=\"buddhistchannel.tv\">[http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=70,4013,0,0,1,0 Gedhun Choekyi Nyima the XIth Panchen Lama turns 18: Still disappeared] The Buddhist Channel, 25 April 2007</ref><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4551425.stm |work = BBC News |title = Tibet's missing spiritual guide |date = 16 May 2005 |accessdate = 3 May 2010}}</ref> and has not been acknowledged in public since 17 May 1995.<ref name=\"buddhistchannel.tv\" /><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\" />\n\n== Selection of the 11th Panchen Lama ==\n{{Tibetan-Chinese-box\n|t = \u0f51\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f51\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f7c\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f49\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\n|w = dge 'dun chos kyi nyi ma\n|ipa = {{IPA-bo|\u0261end\u1ef9 t\u0255\u02b0\u00f8ci \u0272ima}}\n|z = G\u00ead\u00fcn Qoigyi Nyima\n|ts = Gend\u00fcn Ch\u00f6kyi Nyima\n|e = Gedhun Choekyi Nyima\n|tc = \u66f4\u767b\u78ba\u5409\u5c3c\u746a\n|s = \u66f4\u767b\u786e\u5409\u5c3c\u739b\n|p = G\u00e8ngd\u0113ng Qu\u00e8j\u00ed N\u00edm\u01ce\n}}\n{{Tibetan Buddhism}}\n\nFour days before his death, the 10th [[Panchen Lama]] made his own will publicly to follow the tradition. On 24 January, following the opening ceremony of the Ling Pagoda, with religious figures in Tibet, Qinghai, Gansu, Sichuan and Yunnan provinces and autonomous regions, the 10th Penchen Lama held a special talk on the reincarnation of the Living Buddha, proposing that \"the three candidate boys should be identified first and then investigated one by one\" and \"I would like to take the lead by drawing lots of [[Golden Urn]] before the image of Sakyamuni.\" <ref>{{cite news | url = http://blog.wenxuecity.com/blog/frontend.php?act=articlePrint&blogId=29089&date=200711&postId=13943 | title = \u73ed\u7985\u8f6c\u4e16\u7eaa\u5b9e | quote = \u7b2c\u5341\u4e16\u73ed\u7985\u5927\u5e08\u5706\u5bc2\u524d\u56db\u5929\uff0c\u53731\u670824\u65e5\uff0c\u5728\u4e3b\u6301\u7075\u5854\u5f00\u5149\u5178\u793c\u540e\u7684\u897f\u85cf\u3001\u9752\u6d77\u3001\u7518\u8083\u3001\u56db\u5ddd\u3001\u4e91\u5357\u4e94\u7701\u533a\u90e8\u5206\u5b97\u6559\u754c\u4eba\u58eb\u5ea7\u8c08\u4f1a\u4e0a\uff0c\u7279\u522b\u8c08\u4e86\u6d3b\u4f5b\u8f6c\u4e16\u95ee\u9898\uff0c\u63d0\u51fa\u5e94\u201c\u5148\u627e\u51fa\u4e09\u4e2a\u5019\u9009\u7075\u7ae5\uff0c\u7136\u540e\u9010\u4e00\u8fdb\u884c\u8c03\u67e5\u201d\uff0c\u201c\u6211\u60f3\u5728\u91ca\u8fe6\u725f\u5c3c\u50cf\u524d\uff0c\u91c7\u53d6\u2018\u91d1\u74f6\u63a3\u7b7e\u2019\u7684\u529e\u6cd5\u6765\u786e\u5b9a\u3002\u201d\u8fd9\u4e9b\u8bdd\uff0c\u662f\u5927\u5e08\u4e34\u7ec8\u524d\u7684\u9057\u613f\u3002}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the death of the [[10th Panchen Lama]] in 1989, the search for an individual to be recognised as his reincarnation by Tibetan Buddhists quickly became mired in mystery and controversy, as Tibet had been under the [[Annexation of Tibet|occupation and control]] of the anti-religious [[government of the People's Republic of China]] since 1959.<ref>[http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html Gedhun Choekyi Nyima: the XIth Panchen Lama of Tibet] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324212758/http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThree days after the death of the 10th Panchen Lama, the Premier of the State Council published its decision on how the 11th Panchen Lama was to be selected, claiming to have taken advice from the committee of [[Tashi Lhunpo Monastery]] and monks.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://zh.wikisource.org/zh-hans/%E5%9B%BD%E5%8A%A1%E9%99%A2%E5%85%B3%E4%BA%8E%E7%AC%AC%E5%8D%81%E4%B8%96%E7%8F%AD%E7%A6%85%E5%A4%A7%E5%B8%88%E6%B2%BB%E4%B8%A7%E5%92%8C%E8%BD%AC%E4%B8%96%E9%97%AE%E9%A2%98%E7%9A%84%E5%86%B3%E5%AE%9A | title = \u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u5173\u4e8e\u7b2c\u5341\u4e16\u73ed\u7985\u5927\u5e08\u6cbb\u4e27\u548c\u8f6c\u4e16\u95ee\u9898\u7684\u51b3\u5b9a}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.sohu.com/20050412/n225154033.shtml |title = \u7b2c\u5341\u4e16\u73ed\u7985\u5927\u5e08\u7684\u5706\u5bc2\u548c\u9057\u8a00}}</ref>\n\nArmed with Beijing's approval, the head of the Panchen Lama search committee, Chadrel [[Rinpoche]], maintained private communication with the Dalai Lama in order to arrive at a mutually acceptable candidate for both the Dalai Lama and Beijing authorities concerning the Panchen Lama's reincarnation.<ref>[http://www.tchrd.org/press/2001/pr20010824.html TCHRD: Chadrel Rinpoche's fate unknown] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602174257/http://www.tchrd.org/press/2001/pr20010824.html |date=2 June 2008 }}</ref> After the [[Tenzin Gyatso, 14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] named Gedhun Choekyi Nyima as the 11th incarnation of the Panchen Lama on 14 May 1995, Chinese authorities had Chadrel Rinpoche arrested and charged with [[treason]]. According to the Tibetan Government in Exile, he was replaced by Sengchen Lobsang Gyaltsen, so chosen because he was more likely to agree with the [[Communist Party of China|party line]].<ref>[http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov11.html Update-Communist China set to decide on a rival Panchen Lama] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725045825/http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov11.html |date=25 July 2008 }}</ref> Sengchen had been a political opponent of both the [[Tenzin Gyatso, 14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] and the [[10th Panchen Lama]].<ref>[http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov10b.html Communist China set to decide on a rival Panchen Lama] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324003948/http://www.tibet.com/pl/nov10b.html |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref>  Because of the history of rivalry between different sects of Tibetan Buddhism, many Tibetans and scholars believe that this was a tactical move by the [[Chinese Communist Party]] (CCP) to create more unrest and disunity between the typically unified Tibetan peoples.<ref>{{cite web|last=Coonan |first=Clifford |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-appoints-panchen-lama-in-tactical-move-to-quell-unrest-1914309.html |title=China appoints Panchen Lama in tactical move to quell unrest - Asia - World |publisher=The Independent |date=2010-03-02 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://weblog.savetibet.org/2011/08/24/propaganda-and-the-panchen-lama-playing-politics/ |title=Propaganda and the Panchen Lama: playing politics |publisher=Weblog.savetibet.org |date=2011-08-25 |accessdate=2013-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308133516/http://weblog.savetibet.org/2011/08/24/propaganda-and-the-panchen-lama-playing-politics/ |archivedate=8 March 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe new search committee ignored the Dalai Lama's 14 May announcement and instead chose from a list of finalists which excluded Gedhun Choekyi Nyima. In selecting a name, lottery numbers were drawn from a [[Golden Urn]], a procedure used in Tibet by the Chinese (Manchu) emperor in 1793.<ref>Alex McKay, ''The History of Tibet : The Modern Period'', Routledge 2003, {{ISBN|0-415-30844-5}}, p. 32. [https://books.google.com/books?id=3BPsOQe654IC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA32#v=onepage Google books]</ref> The 14th Dalai Lama stated that the Tibetan method involves using possessions of the former Lama to identify his reincarnation, as the new child incarnate will reportedly recognize his past items amid miscellaneous ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dalailama.com/biography/reincarnation |title=Reincarnation &#124; The Office of His Holiness The Dalai Lama |publisher=Dalailama.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref> On January 26, 1940, the Regent Reting Rinpoche requested the Central Government to exempt Tenzin Gyatso from the lot-drawing process of the [[Golden Urn]] to become the 14th Dalai Lama.<ref name=\"Goldstein1991\">{{cite book|author=Melvyn C. Goldstein|title=A History of Modern Tibet, 1913-1951: The Demise of the Lamaist State|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Upwq0I-wm7YC&pg=PA328|date=18 June 1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-91176-5|pages=328 ff.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livingbuddha.us.com/view-d59c6c9eba6e4beb842b893f40fdec75.html|title=Report to Wu Zhongxin from the Regent Reting Rinpoche Regarding the Process of Searching and Recognizing the Thirteenth Dalai lama's Reincarnated Soul Boy as well as the Request for an Exemption to Drawing Lots - - The Reincarnation of Living Buddhas|website=www.livingbuddha.us.com}}</ref> The request was approved by the Central Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livingbuddha.us.com/view-54a211e996dd4f9fa9671e9489317a42.html|title=The National Government's Decree on the Special Approval of Recognizing Lhamo Thondup as the Fourteenth Dalai Lama with an Exemption of Drawing Lots and the Appropriation of the Expenditure for His Enthronement - - The Reincarnation of Living Buddhas|website=www.livingbuddha.us.com}}</ref> Chinese authorities announced [[Gyancain Norbu]] as the search committee's choice on 11 November 1995.<ref>Isabel Hilton, A Reporter at Large, \"Spies in the House of Faith,\" The New Yorker, 23 August 1999, p. 170</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC]] reported that the CCP's choice of [[Gyancain Norbu]] was rejected by most Tibetans.<ref>{{Cite news |title = Tibet's missing spiritual guide |work = BBC |accessdate = 15 November 2010 |date = 16 May 2005 |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4551425.stm}}</ref> Alexander Norman wrote, \"Today, the Panchen Lamas are famous for having two claimants to the [[wikt:see#Noun|see]] of [[Tashi Lhunpo Monastery|Tashilhunpo]]: one recognised by the present [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]] and taken into [[house arrest]] by the Chinese, the other recognised by China but by no one else.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Norman|first1=Alexander|title=Holder of the White Lotus: The Lives of the Dalai Lama|date=2008|publisher=Little, Brown|location=London|isbn=978-0-316-85988-2|page=165}}</ref>\n\n== Whereabouts ==\nSince his selection, the whereabouts of Gedhun Choekyi Nyima have been unknown.<ref>{{cite web |last=Coonan |first=Clifford |url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/china-appoints-panchen-lama-in-tactical-move-to-quell-unrest-1914309.html |title=China appoints Panchen Lama in tactical move to quell unrest - Asia - World |publisher=The Independent |date=2010-03-02 |accessdate=2013-12-25}}</ref> Officials state that his whereabouts are kept undisclosed to protect him.<ref>[http://www.xizang-zhiye.org/gb/xzxinwen/0504/index.html Xizang-zhiye 27 April 2005] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060824025010/http://www.xizang-zhiye.org/gb/xzxinwen/0504/index.html|date=24 August 2006}}</ref> [[Human Rights|Human rights]] organizations termed him the \"youngest [[political prisoner]] in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/23/AR2006042301349.html |title=World's youngest political prisoner turns 17 |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=2006-04-23 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref><ref>Laird, Thomas (2006). ''The Story of Tibet: Conversations with the Dalai Lama'', p 374. Grove Press, N.Y. {{ISBN|978-0-8021-1827-1}}.</ref> No foreign party has been allowed to visit him.<ref name=\"KumarTestimony\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foreign.senate.gov/publications/download/testimony-of-mr-t-kumar-us-china-relations|title=Amnesty International Testimony US \u2013 China Relations before the Committee on Foreign Relations United States Senate by T. Kumar, Advocacy Director for Asia|date=11 September 2003|publisher=US Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Committee on the Rights of the Child]] requested to be told of Nyima's whereabouts on 28 May 1996. ''[[Xinhua]]'' declined, responding that Nyima was at risk of being \"kidnapped by separatists\" and that \"his security had been threatened\".<ref>[http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html Site of the TCHRD] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324212758/http://www.tchrd.org/publications/brochures/panchen_lama_XI-2005.html |date=24 March 2008 }}</ref> The Committee requested a visit with Gedhun Choekyi Nyima, supported by a campaign of more than 400 celebrities and associations petitioning for the visit, including six [[Nobel Prize]] winners.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.tibet.fr/old/panchen_appel.htm |title=Appel Pour Le Plus Jeune Prisonnier Politique Du Monde |publisher=Tibet.fr |date=1995-05-14 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref><ref name=\"UNPO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unpo.org/content/view/3948/84/ |title=UNPO \u2013 WS on Panchen Lamas Case |publisher=Unpo.org |date=2006-03-09 |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref> According to statements by the Chinese government from 1998, he was then leading a normal life.<ref name=\"KumarTestimony\" />\n\nIn May 2007, [[Asma Jahangir]], Special Rapporteur on Freedom of Religion or Belief of the [[UN Human Rights Council]], asked the Chinese authorities what measures they had taken to implement the recommendation of the Committee on the Rights of the Child, that the government should allow an independent expert to visit and confirm the well-being of Gedhun Choekyi Nyima while respecting his right to privacy, and that of his parents. In a response dated 17 July 2007, the Chinese authorities said: \"Gedhun Choekyi Nyima is a perfectly ordinary Tibetan boy, in an excellent state of health, leading a normal, happy life and receiving a good education and cultural upbringing. He is currently in upper secondary school, he measures {{cvt|165|cm|ftin|disp=sqbr}} in height and is easy-going by nature. He studies hard and his school results are very good. He likes Chinese traditional culture and has recently taken up calligraphy. His parents are both State employees, and his brothers and sisters are either already working or at university. The allegation that he disappeared together with his parents and that his whereabouts remain unknown is simply not true.\" This response did not answer the question about a visit or confirmation.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.phayul.com/news/article.aspx?id=20897&article=China+Fails+to+Respond+to+UN+Rights+Expert's+Question+on+Panchen+Lama&t=1&c=1 |title=China Fails to Respond to UN Rights Expert's Question on Panchen Lama |date=25 April 2008 |accessdate=28 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, on the twentieth anniversary of Gendun Choekyi Nyima's disappearance, Chinese officials announced \"The reincarnated child Panchen Lama you mentioned is being educated, living a normal life, growing up healthily and does not wish to be disturbed.\"<ref>{{cite web |title = China says Panchen Lama 'living a normal life' 20 years after disappearance |url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/06/china-says-panchen-lama-living-a-normal-life-20-years-after-disappearance |publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=September 6, 2015 |accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the [[Dalai Lama]] declared that he knew from a \"reliable source\" that the Panchen Lama he had recognized, Gedhun Choekyi Nyima, was alive and receiving normal education. He said he hoped that the PRC appointed Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.<ref>[https://www.thestatesman.com/india/11th-panchen-lama-alive-receiving-education-dalai-lama-1502627372.html 11th Panchen Lama alive, receiving education: Dalai Lama], ''The Statesman'', April 25, 2018: \"Tibetan spiritual leader Dalai Lama on Wednesday said 11th Panchen Lama Gedhun Choekyi Nyima \u201caccording to reliable source is alive and receiving normal education\u201d. Talking to the media at Gaggal Airport in Kangra district after returning from four-day Delhi visit, Lama hoped that the official Panchen Lama studies well under the guidance of a good teacher. \u201cThen the Panchen Lama, which I recognised sometime back, there was no news, but then according to reliable information, he is still alive and receiving normal education. So we will see,\u201d he said. He said there are instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, \u201cwhere a reincarnated lama took more than one manifestation\u201d.\"</ref><ref>Dr. Andrea Galli, [https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2018/05/09/dalai-lama-and-the-panchen-lama-quarrel-the-way-for-rapprochement-with-china/ Dalai Lama and the Panchen Lama quarrel: The way for rapprochement with China], ''Modern Diplomacy'', May 9, 2018.</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Gedhun Choekyi Nyima [[Forced disappearance|has not been seen by any independent observer since his disappearance]] in 1995.<ref>[http://www.tibetanreview.net/dalai-lama-cites-reliable-source-as-saying-panchen-lama-alive-speaks-well-for-the-chinese-appointed-counter/ Dalai Lama cites \u2018reliable source\u2019 as saying Panchen Lama alive, speaks well for the Chinese appointed counter], ''[[Tibetan Review]]'', April 27, 2018  : \"Following the passing away of the 10th Panchen Lama Choekyi Gyaltsen in Jan 1989, Tibet\u2019s exiled spiritual leader formally proclaimed six-year-old Gedhun Choekyi Nyima born in Tibet as his undisputed reincarnation on May 14, 1995. Three days later, the Chinese government took him and his family away to be never seen or heard from again.\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously: post-1970|List of people who disappeared]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4551425.stm BBC News article \u2013 \"Tibet's missing spiritual guide\"]\n\n{{-}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Panchen Lama]]|1989|April 25}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Choekyi Gyaltsen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Panchen Lama|Reincarnation of the Panchen Lama]]<br /><small>([[Government of Tibet in Exile]] interpretation)|years=1995\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Panchen Lamas |state = uncollapsed }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nyima, Gedhun Choekyi}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:Forced disappearances in China]]\n[[Category:Panchen Lamas|Panchen Lama XI]]\n[[Category:People from Nagqu]]\n", "name_user": "Numberguy6", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gedhun_Choekyi_Nyima"}
{"title_page": "Chandler River (New South Wales)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Chandler River (disambiguation){{!}}Chandler River}}\n{{distinguish|Chandlers Creek}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2013}}{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Chandler River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = named by [[John Saumarez Dumaresq|Captain Dumaresq]] in honour of one of his [[stockmen]]<ref name=gnb>{{NSW GNR |id=JPqwWysEJP |title=Chandler River |date=17 March 1967 |accessdate=3 June 2011 }}</ref>\n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Halls Peak Mine02.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| image_caption      = Halls Peak Mine and the Chandler River in [[Oxley Wild Rivers National Park]]\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Australia]]\n| subdivision_type2  = [[States and territories of Australia|State]]\n| subdivision_name2  = [[New South Wales]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[New England Tablelands (biographic region)|New England Tablelands]] ([[Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia|IBRA]]), [[Northern Tablelands]]\n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = [[Local government in Australia|Local government area]]\n| subdivision_name5  = [[Armidale Dumaresq Shire|Armidale Dumaresq]]\n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|110|km|mi|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= \n| discharge1_min     = \n| discharge1_avg     = \n| discharge1_max     = \n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = [[Great Dividing Range]]\n| source1_location   = northeast of [[Armidale, New South Wales|Armidale]] and southeast of [[Guyra, New South Wales|Guyra]]\n| source1_coordinates= \n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|1260|m|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[confluence]] with the [[Macleay River]]\n| mouth_location     = below Table Top Mountain, within [[Cunnawarra National Park]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = \n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|210|m|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = [[Macleay River]] catchment\n| basin_size         = \n| tributaries_left   = Chandalina Creek, Maiden Creek (New South Wales), Station Creek (New South Wales), [[Oaky River]], [[Styx River (New South Wales)|Styx River]]\n| tributaries_right  = [[Wollomombi River]]\n| custom_label       = [[Waterfall]]\n| custom_data        = Chandler Falls\n| extra              = <ref name=bonzle>{{cite web |url=http://www.bonzle.com/c/a?a=p&p=207526&cmd=sp |title=Map of Chandler River, NSW |publisher=Bonzle Digital Atlas of Australia |accessdate=4 March 2013 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Chandler River''', a [[perennial stream]] of the [[Macleay River]] catchment, is located in the [[Northern Tablelands]] district of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].\n\n==Course and features==\nChandler River rises on the eastern slopes of the [[Great Dividing Range]], northeast of [[Armidale, New South Wales|Armidale]] and southeast of [[Guyra, New South Wales|Guyra]], and flows generally southerly, joined by six [[tributary|tributaries]] including the [[Wollomombi River|Wollomombi]], [[Oaky River|Oaky]], and [[Styx River (New South Wales)|Styx]] rivers, before reaching its [[confluence]] with the Macleay River, south of the [[Cunnawarra National Park]], below Table Top Mountain within the [[Oxley Wild Rivers National Park]]. The river descends {{convert|1050|m}} over its {{convert|111|km}} [[watercourse|course]].<ref name=bonzle/>\n\nWithin both the Cunnawarra and Oxley Wild Rivers national parks, the Chandler River passes through a number of spectacular [[Canyon|gorges]] and [[waterfalls]], including the Chandler Falls. Although not on the Chandler River, the [[Wollomombi Falls]] is located just east of the Chandler River, shortly before its confluence with the Wollomombi River. At the Wollomombi Falls lookout there are scenic gorge rim walks and a steep [[trail#Walking trails|walking-track]] that descends into the Chandler River valley floor.\n\nElsewhere, Halls Peak camping area is situated on the banks of the Chandler River and caters for self-reliant visitors looking to experience the seclusion of remote camping in a rural setting.  The [[trail]] to the camp site is very steep, descending almost {{convert|700|m}}. Steep sides of the trail do not have safety protection barriers. The [[National Parks and Wildlife Service (New South Wales)|NSW National Parks & Wildlife Service]] (NPWS) recommends, as a minimum, the use of high clearance low-range 4WD vehicles with a skilled experienced driver.  A fee is payable and a key must be obtained at the Armidale office of the NPWS.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.getaboutnewsouthwales.com.au/NSW/NationalParks/NationalParksInfo.php?nationalPark=Oxley+Wild+Rivers+National+Park&location=Halls+Peak+Campground&latLng=-30.73917%2C+152.04882&id=102 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324225113/http://www.getaboutnewsouthwales.com.au/NSW/NationalParks/NationalParksInfo.php?nationalPark=Oxley+Wild+Rivers+National+Park&location=Halls+Peak+Campground&latLng=-30.73917,+152.04882&id=102 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 March 2012 |title=Halls Peak Campground: Oxley Wild Rivers National Park |work=Get About Australia |publisher=Tourism Australia |accessdate=3 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nChandler River is transversed by the [[Waterfall Way]] near [[Wollomombi, New South Wales|Wollomombi]].\n\nChandler River was named by [[John Saumarez Dumaresq|Captain Dumaresq]] in honour of one of his [[stockmen]]<ref name=gnb/>\n\nOn the upper reaches of the river beef cattle [[grazing|graze]]; while [[Brumby|brumbies]] roam the lower reaches of the river.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|New South Wales}}\n{{Commons category|Chandler River}}\n*[[Wollomombi Falls]]\n*[[List of rivers of Australia]]\n*[[Rivers of New South Wales]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://crcleme.org.au/RegExpOre/HallsPeak.pdf  Map and mine locations]\n\n{{Rivers of New South Wales |state=autocollapse}}\n{{coord|30|37|S|152|00|E|display=title|region:AU_type:river_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Northern Tablelands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Chandler River (disambiguation){{!}}Chandler River}}\n{{distinguish|Chandlers Creek}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2013}}{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox river\n| name               = Chandler River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = named by [[John Saumarez Dumaresq|Captain Dumaresq]] in honour of one of his [[stockmen]]<ref name=gnb>{{NSW GNR |id=JPqwWysEJP |title=Chandler River |date=17 March 1967 |accessdate=3 June 2011 }}</ref>\n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Halls Peak Mine02.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| image_caption      = Halls Peak Mine and the Chandler River in [[Oxley Wild Rivers National Park]]\n| map                = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = \n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[Australia]]\n| subdivision_type2  = [[States and territories of Australia|State]]\n| subdivision_name2  = [[New South Wales]]\n| subdivision_type3  = Region\n| subdivision_name3  = [[New England Tablelands (biographic region)|New England Tablelands]] ([[Interim Biogeographic Regionalisation for Australia|IBRA]]), [[Northern Tablelands]]\n| subd