| utc_offset                      = \n| timezone_DST                    = \n| utc_offset_DST                  = <!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = \n| website                         = [http://125.209.91.254/CDGK/LinkClick.aspx?link=207&tabid=72 Landhi Town Page]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n| extinct_title                   = Disbanded\n| extinct_date                    = 2011\n}}\n'''Landhi Town''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0688\u06be\u06cc \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646}}}}) was a [[Towns in Karachi|Karachi borough]] in the eastern part of the city that was named after the locality of [[Landhi]]. Landhi Town was formed in 2001 as part of [https://web.archive.org/web/20081013065059/http://www.nrb.gov.pk/city_district/index.html The Local Government Ordinance 2001], and was subdivided into 9 [[Union councils of Pakistan|Union Councils]]. The Town system and was disbanded in 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribe.com/2011/07/11/karachi%e2%80%99s-district-status-restored-notification-issued/|title=Karachi\u2019s district status restored, notification issued|last=Abbasi|first=Saeed|date=2011-07-10|website=The News Tribe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and Korangi Town was re-organized as part of [[Karachi East District]], before [[Korangi District]] was formed.\n\n== Location ==\nIt is bordered by the [[Faisal Cantonment]] and [[Shah Faisal Town]] to the north across the [[Malir River]], [[Bin Qasim Town]] to the south and east, and [[Korangi Town]] to the west. The population of Landhi Town was estimated to be over 660,000 at the 1998 census, of which 99% are [[Muslim]]. Sindhis and Pashtuns constitute an overwhelming majority of the population, followed by Muhajirs and Baloch.\n\n== History ==\nLandhi Town contained much of the oldest parts of Karachi.  The federal government under [[Pervez Musharraf]], who seized power in a [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999 coup d'etat]], introduced local government reforms in the year 2000, which eliminated the previous \"third tier of government\" ([[Divisions of Pakistan|administrative divisions]]) and replaced it with the fourth tier ([[Districts of Pakistan|districts]]). The effect in Karachi was the dissolution of the former [[Karachi Division]], and the merging of its five districts to form a new Karachi City-District with eighteen autonomous constituent towns including Landhi Town. In 2011, the system was disbanded but remained in place for bureaucratic administration until 2015, when the [[Karachi Metropolitan Corporation]] system was reintroduced. In 2015, Landhi Town was re-organized as part of [[Karachi East]], before it was made part of [[Korangi District]].\n\n== Neighbourhoods ==\n\n* Awami Colony\n* Bhutto Nagar is named after former [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister]] [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]], a Sindhi.\n* Sher Pao Colony\n* Dawood Chowrangi\n* Khawaja Ajmeer Colony  is named after [[Khwaja Moinuddin Chishti]] of [[Ajmer]].\n* Burmee Colony is named for the [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]] refugees who hail from [[Myanmar]] (formerly [[Burma]]).\n* Korangi lies on the eastern side of Karachi between Karachi and Keti Bandar \u2013 the area extending from Korangi to Rehri Creek.\n* Landhi is home to Babar Market, one of Asia's largest open air markets. [[Landhi railway station]] is also located in this area.\n* Moinabad\n* Muslimabad\n* Majeed Colony\n* Muzafarabad\n* Sharafi Goth\n* Sherabad\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Landhi Industrial Area]]\n* [[City District Government]]\n* [[Karachi]]\n* [[Lahore]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.karachicity.gov.pk Karachi Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060219152737/http://www.karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Landhi Landhi Town]\n\n{{Karachi Towns}}\n{{Karachi topics}}\n\n[[Category:Landhi Town| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copy editing.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landhi_Town"}
{"title_page": "Treaty of Madrid (1667)", "text_new": "{{other uses|Treaty of Madrid (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Neutrality and commercial agreement between England and Spain}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                 = Treaty of Madrid\n| long_name            =\n| image                = Edward Montagu.jpeg\n| image_width          = 250px\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Edward Montagu, Earl of Sandwich]]\n| context              = [[Habsburg Spain|Spain]] and [[Kingdom of England|England]] undertake not to assist enemies of the other; England agrees to mediate an end to the [[Portuguese Restoration War]]; Spain awards England commercial privileges\n| date_drafted         =\n| date_signed          = {{Start date|df=yes|1667|05|23}}\n| location_signed      = [[Madrid]]\n| date_sealed          =\n| date_effective       =\n| condition_effective  = 21 September 1667\n| date_expiration      =\n| date_expiry          =\n| mediators            =\n| negotiators          = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Fanshawe]] <br> {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Earl of Sandwich]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Gaspar Juan P\u00e9rez de Guzm\u00e1n, 10th Duke of Medina Sidonia|Medina Sidonia]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Juan Everardo Nithard|Juan Nithard]]\n| original_signatories =\n| signatories          = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Earl of Sandwich]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Gaspar de Bracamonte, 3rd Count of Pe\u00f1aranda|Count Pe\u00f1aranda]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} Count O\u00f1ate\n| parties              = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of England}} <br> {{Flagcountry|Spain|1506}}\n| ratifiers            = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Charles II of England]]  <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Mariana of Austria]] for [[Charles II of Spain]]\n| depositor            =\n| depositories         =\n| citations            =\n| language             = Latin\n| languages            =\n| wikisource           =\n| wikisource1          =\n| footnotes            =\n}}\n\nThe '''Treaty of Madrid''', also known as '''The Earl of Sandwich's Treaty''', was signed on 23 May, 1667 by [[Kingdom of England|England]] and [[Habsburg Spain|Spain]]. It was one of a series of agreements made in response to French expansion under [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]].\n\nThe parties agreed commercial terms allowing English merchants trading privileges within the [[Spanish Empire]], which remained in place until superseded by the [[Treaty of Utrecht]] in 1714. They undertook not to assist each other's enemies, while England also agreed to mediate an end to the 1640 to 1668 [[Portuguese Restoration War]]; this resulted in the [[Treaty of Lisbon (1668)|1668 Treaty of Lisbon]] between Spain and [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]].\n\nThe issue of Spanish possessions captured by England in the [[Anglo-Spanish War (1654\u20131660)|1654 to 1660 Anglo-Spanish War]] were settled in the subsequent [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|1670 Treaty of Madrid]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:AMH-6748-NA Two views of the English fort in Bombay.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bombay]], c. 1665; acquired by [[Charles II of England|Charles]]' marriage to [[Catherine of Braganza]], which disrupted Anglo-Spanish relations]]\nThe treaty was one of a series of agreements signed between 1662 to 1668, driven by changes in the European balance of power. These included the weakening of the relationship between France and the [[Dutch Republic]], allies in the 1568 to 1648 [[Eighty Years War]], and Spain's eclipse by [[Kingdom of France|France]] under [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]].{{sfn|Israel|1990|pp=197-198}}\n\nBy the middle of the 17th century, the [[Spanish Empire]] remained a huge global confederation but needed peace after a century of continuous warfare. The 1635 to 1659 [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u201359)|Franco-Spanish War]] concluded with the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]]; the [[Anglo-Spanish War (1654\u20131660)|1654 to 1660 war]] with the [[Commonwealth of England]] was suspended after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration of Charles II]] in 1660.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|p=50}}\n\nSpain now focused on ending the long-running [[Portuguese Restoration War]]; in [[Treaty of Brussels (1656)|1656]], [[Philip IV of Spain|Philip IV]] agreed to help [[Charles II of England|Charles]] regain his throne, in return for assistance against Portugal. However, in [[Marriage Treaty|May 1661]], Charles agreed to marry [[Catherine of Braganza]] and provide Portugal [[English expedition to Portugal (1662\u20131668)|military support]].{{sfn|Belcher|1975|pp=70-71}}\n\nThis was the result of various factors, one being Philip's insistence on the return of [[Jamaica]], captured in 1656, and [[Siege of Dunkirk (1658)|Dunkirk]], captured in 1658; previously part of the [[Spanish Netherlands]], Charles sold it to France in 1662. Relinquishing Jamaica was viewed with great hostility in England, where [[Parliament of England|Parliament]] voted to annex it in September 1660. English merchants gained access to Portuguese markets in [[Colonial Brazil|Brazil]], Africa and the Far East; the acquisition of [[English Tangier|Tangier]] and [[Bombay]] provided bases in the [[Mediterranean]] and on the [[Surat]] coast. This made it too attractive to refuse but impacted Anglo-Spanish relations.{{sfn|Belcher|1975|pp=72-73}}\n\n==Negotiations==\n[[File:Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|[[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Fanshawe]], English ambassador in [[Lisbon]] (1662-1666) and [[Madrid]], 1664 to 1666; his negotiations were the basis of the 1667 treaty]]\n[[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Fanshawe]], English [[List of ambassadors of the Kingdom of England to Portugal|ambassador in Portugal]] from 1662 to 1666, was also appointed [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Spain|ambassador to Spain]] in 1664. He was instructed to agree a treaty of commerce, obtain reparations for losses and confirm possession of territories captured from 1654 to 1660, primarily [[Jamaica]].{{sfn|Riley|2014|p=58}}\n\nIn 1663, Philip launched a major military offensive against Portugal and refused to negotiate while England was assisting 'rebels'.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|p=94}} Talks opened in 1664 when the offensive failed, halted when the [[Second Anglo-Dutch War]] began in March 1665, then restarted following Spanish defeat at the [[Battle of Montes Claros]] in June.{{sfn|Riley|2014|pp=122-123}} Philip died in September, leaving his three year old son [[Charles II of Spain|Charles II]] as king, and his wife [[Mariana of Austria]] as regent.{{sfn|Cowans|2003|pp=26\u201327}}\n[[File:El cardenal Juan Everardo Nithard.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Juan Everardo Nithard|Juan Nithard]], Spanish chief minister]]\nEnding the war with Portugal was a priority for the new Spanish government and [[Juan Everardo Nithard|Juan Nithard]] made an Anglo-Spanish treaty dependent on English help in achieving this. However, Louis encouraged Portugal to insist on harsh terms, seeking to prevent Spain reinforcing the Spanish Netherlands.{{sfn|Geyl|1936|pp=311-312}}\n\nIn December, Fanshawe finalised terms with [[Gaspar de Bracamonte, 3rd Count of Pe\u00f1aranda|Count Pe\u00f1aranda]], a member of the Spanish Regency Council, using the 1630 Treaty of Madrid as a base. They were unaware of discussions in London between the Spanish ambassador, Count Molina, the [[James II of England|Duke of York]] and [[Henry Bennet, 1st Earl of Arlington|Arlington]]. Charles refused to ratify Fanshawe's version, claiming he had exceeded instructions and replaced him with [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Lord Sandwich]]. Fanshawe died in June 1666, shortly before returning home.{{sfn|Lockey|2016|p=260}}\n\nIn March 1667, France and Portugal signed the [[Treaty of Lisbon (1667)|Treaty of Lisbon]], a ten year offensive and defensive alliance against Spain; on 24 May, French troops entered the Spanish Netherlands in the [[War of Devolution]]. Facing the prospect of another ten years of war with Portugal and the loss of their provinces to France, Spain now quickly came to terms.{{sfn|Feiling|2013|pp=232-234}}\n\n==Terms==\nThe prominence of commercial issues in 17th and 18th century diplomacy derived from the economic theory of [[Mercantilism]], which viewed global trade as finite. Increasing your share meant taking it from others, so states protected their own using [[tariff]]s or import bans, while attacking the colonies or ships of others.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rothbard|first1=Murray|title=Mercantilism as the Economic Side of Absolutism|url=https://mises.org/library/mercantilism-economic-side-absolutism|website=Mises.org|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> English complaints related to two areas; exclusion from markets within the [[Spanish Empire]], and restrictions on direct trade between mainland Spain and England.{{sfn|McLachlan|1934|p=299}}\n\nThe 1630 treaty was annulled and on 23 May 1667, England and Spain signed two new treaties; a commercial deal and an agreement by England to mediate a truce between Portugal and Spain.{{sfn|Fisher, Savelle|1967|pp=66-70}} In a separate article, each party undertook not to assist enemies of the other; England would withdraw its Portuguese expeditionary force, while Spain remained neutral in the Anglo-Dutch war.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|pp=96-98}}\n[[File:Potassium nitrate.jpg|thumb|left|upright|180px|[[Saltpetre]]; used in [[gunpowder]], it was hugely profitable for the [[East India Company]], a major beneficiary of the treaty]]\nThe commercial treaty consisted of forty separate articles, the most important being '''Article Seven''', part of Fanshawe's draft but omitted from the original terms.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|pp=96-98}} English merchants were given equal status with the Dutch and granted the right to import goods tax free into European Spain.{{sfn|Andrien, Kuethe|2014|pp=50-52}} '''Articles Seven, Eight, Eleven and Twelve''' went further than this, by allowing [[Thirteen Colonies|English colonies in North America]] and the [[East India Company]] to ship goods direct to Spanish ports.{{sfn|McLachlan|1934|p=299}}\n\nBy granting English merchants trading rights within Spanish America, the treaty accepted England's presence in the Caribbean and occupation of Jamaica, although this was not formally recognised until 1670. '''Article Ten''' broadly exempted English ships and warehouses in Spanish ports from customs inspections, disputes being referred to a local judge, nominated by the English and confirmed by Madrid.{{sfn|Andrien, Kuethe|2014|p=50}}\n\n'''Articles Fourteen through Seventeen''' allowed English ships access to ports throughout the Spanish Empire, a significant concession since it greatly increased their operating range.{{sfn|McLachlan|1934|p=299}} '''Article Thirty-Eight''' made English merchants equivalent to the Dutch and French by awarding them [[most favoured nation]] status; its implementation was resisted by Spanish merchants and had to be re-iterated in the [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|1670 Treaty]].{{sfn|Stein, Stein|2000|p=63}} \n\nThese concessions were the first step in challenging Dutch economic supremacy outside Europe and thus of greater significance than often appreciated; they remained in place until the outbreak of the [[War of the Spanish Succession]] in 1701.{{sfn|Lodge|1932|p=3}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:An English Merchant Ship in a Mediterranean Harbour in a Light Breeze with Many Other Vessels RMG BHC0890.tiff|thumb|right|200px|English ship in harbour, ca 1680; the treaty allowed access to ports throughout the Spanish Empire ]]\nEconomic historian Guillermo P\u00e9rez Sarri\u00f3n claims the 1667 treaty demonstrates 'England's absolute dominance of Anglo-Spanish trade'.{{sfn|Sarrion|2016|p=57}} One London merchant later described it as \u2018the best flower in our garden'; English goods were imported through [[Cadiz]], then sold locally or re-exported to the colonies, Spanish dye and wool going the other way.{{sfn|Mclachlan|1940|p=6}}\n\nFranco-Spanish trade primarily consisted of bulk imports like grain and timber, which were easily regulated by local authorities. English trade was predominantly maritime, within the vast Spanish Empire, and much harder to control; the treaty effectively permitted ships captains to decide what goods were listed on their [[Manifest (transportation)|manifest]] as 'English'.{{sfn| Sarrion|2016|p=58}} This allowed English merchants to evade customs duties, demand from Spanish colonists creating a large and extremely profitable [[black market]].{{sfn|Richmond|1920|p=2}}\n\nIn September, [[Afonso VI of Portugal]] was deposed in a coup led by his brother [[Peter II of Portugal|Pedro]]; the previous treaty with France was annulled and with England as mediator, Spain and Portugal signed the [[Treaty of Lisbon (1668)|Treaty of Lisbon]] on 13 February 1668.{{sfn|Newitt|2004|p=228}} Relieved of this burden and backed by the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]], Spain ended the War of Devolution with France by agreeing the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1668)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]] on 5 May.{{sfn|Davenport, Paulin|1917|p=144}}\n\nThe question of Spanish possessions in the [[West Indies]] captured by England in 1654 to 1660 was later settled in the [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|1670 Treaty of Madrid]].{{sfn|Fisher, Savelle|1967|pp=66-70}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Andrien|first1=Kenneth J|last2=Kuethe|first2=Allan J|title=The Spanish Atlantic World in the Eighteenth Century: War and the Bourbon Reforms, 1713\u20131796|date=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9781107043572|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Belcher |first1=Gerald |title=Spain and the Anglo-Portuguese Alliance of 1661: A Reassessment of Charles II's Foreign Policy at the Restoration |journal=British Studies |date=1975 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=67\u201388 |doi=10.1086/385679 |jstor=175239 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cowans|first1=Jon|title=Modern Spain: A Documentary History|year=2003|publisher=U. of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-1846-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Davenport|editor1-first=Frances Gardiner|editor2-last=Paullin|editor2-first=Charles Oscar|title=European Treaties Bearing on the History of the United States and Its Dependencies, Vol. 2: 1650-1697|date=1917|publisher=Forgotten Books|isbn=978-0483158924|edition=2018|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Feiling|first1=Keith|title=British Foreign Policy 1660-1972|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136241543|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Fisher|first1=Margaret Anne|last2=Savelle|first2=Max|title=The origins of American diplomacy: the international history of Angloamerica, 1492-1763 American diplomatic history series Authors|date=1967|publisher=Macmillan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Xxd2AAAAMAAJ&dq=|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Geyl |first1=P |title=Johan de Witt, Grand Pensionary of Holland, 1653\u201372 |journal=History |date=1936 |volume=20 |issue=80 |pages=303\u2013319 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-229X.1936.tb00103.x |jstor=24401084 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Israel|first1=Jonathan|title=Dutch Primacy in World Trade, 1585\u20131740|date=1989|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0198211396|ref=harv|edition=1990}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Lockey|first1=Brian C|title=Early Modern Catholics, Royalists, and Cosmopolitans: English Transnationalism and the Christian Commonwealth Transculturalisms, 1400-1700|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317147107|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Lodge |first1=Richard |title=Presidential Address: Sir Benjamin Keene, K.B.: A Study in Anglo-Spanish Relations in the Earlier Part of the Eighteenth Century|journal=Transactions of the Royal Historical Society |date=1932 |volume=15 |pages=1\u201343 |ref=harv |doi=10.2307/3678642|jstor=3678642 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Mclachlan |first1=Jean O |title=Trade and Peace with Old Spain |date=1940 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1107585614 |ref=harv |edition=2015}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=McLachlan |first1=Jean |title=Documents Illustrating Anglo-Spanish Trade between the Commercial Treaty of 1667 and the Commercial Treaty and the Asiento Contract of 1713 |journal=Cambridge Historical Journal |date=1934 |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=299\u2013311 |doi=10.1017/S1474691300000664 |jstor=3020673 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Newitt|first1=Malyn|title=A History of Portuguese Overseas Expansion 1400\u20131668|date=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134553044|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Richmond |first1=Herbert |title=The Navy in the War of 1739-48 - War College Series |date=1920 |publisher=War College Series |isbn=978-1296326296 |ref=harv |edition=2015}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Riley|first1=Jonathon|title=The Last Ironsides: The English Expedition to Portugal, 1662-1668|date=2014|publisher=Helion & Company|isbn=978-1909982208|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Sarrion |first1=Guillermo Perez |title=The Emergence of a National Market in Spain, 1650-1800: Trade Networks, Foreign Powers and the State |date=2016 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=9781472586469}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Stein|first1=Stanley J|last2=Stein|first2=Barbara H|title=Silver, Trade, and War: Spain and America in the Making of Early Modern Europe|date=2000|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=9780801861352|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mypl8up1eMwC&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=}}\n\n[[Category:Treaties of England]]\n[[Category:1667 in England]]\n[[Category:1667 treaties]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Spanish Empire]]\n[[Category:History of Madrid]]\n[[Category:17th century in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:1667 in Spain]]\n[[Category:1667 in the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Treaty of Madrid (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Neutrality and commercial agreement between England and Spain}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                 = Treaty of Madrid\n| long_name            =\n| image                = Edward Montagu.jpeg\n| image_width          = 170px\n| image_alt            =\n| caption              = [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Edward Montagu, Earl of Sandwich]]\n| context              = [[Habsburg Spain|Spain]] and [[Kingdom of England|England]] undertake not to assist enemies of the other; England agrees to mediate an end to the [[Portuguese Restoration War]]; Spain awards England commercial privileges\n| date_drafted         =\n| date_signed          = {{Start date|df=yes|1667|05|23}}\n| location_signed      = [[Madrid]]\n| date_sealed          =\n| date_effective       =\n| condition_effective  = 21 September 1667\n| date_expiration      =\n| date_expiry          =\n| mediators            =\n| negotiators          = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Fanshawe]] <br> {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Earl of Sandwich]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Gaspar Juan P\u00e9rez de Guzm\u00e1n, 10th Duke of Medina Sidonia|Medina Sidonia]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Juan Everardo Nithard|Juan Nithard]]\n| original_signatories =\n| signatories          = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Earl of Sandwich]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Gaspar de Bracamonte, 3rd Count of Pe\u00f1aranda|Count Pe\u00f1aranda]] <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} Count O\u00f1ate\n| parties              = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of England}} <br> {{Flagcountry|Spain|1506}}\n| ratifiers            = {{flagicon|Kingdom of England}} [[Charles II of England]]  <br> {{Flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Mariana of Austria]] for [[Charles II of Spain]]\n| depositor            =\n| depositories         =\n| citations            =\n| language             = Latin\n| languages            =\n| wikisource           =\n| wikisource1          =\n| footnotes            =\n}}\n\nThe '''Treaty of Madrid''', also known as '''The Earl of Sandwich's Treaty''', was signed on 23 May, 1667 by [[Kingdom of England|England]] and [[Habsburg Spain|Spain]]. It was one of a series of agreements made in response to French expansion under [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]].\n\nThe parties agreed commercial terms allowing English merchants trading privileges within the [[Spanish Empire]], which remained in place until superseded by the [[Treaty of Utrecht]] in 1714. They undertook not to assist each other's enemies, while England also agreed to mediate an end to the 1640 to 1668 [[Portuguese Restoration War]]; this resulted in the [[Treaty of Lisbon (1668)|1668 Treaty of Lisbon]] between Spain and [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]].\n\nThe issue of Spanish possessions captured by England in the [[Anglo-Spanish War (1654\u20131660)|1654 to 1660 Anglo-Spanish War]] were settled in the subsequent [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|1670 Treaty of Madrid]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:AMH-6748-NA Two views of the English fort in Bombay.jpg|thumb|left|160px|[[Bombay]], c. 1665; acquired by [[Charles II of England|Charles]]' marriage to [[Catherine of Braganza]], which disrupted Anglo-Spanish relations]]\nThe treaty was one of a series of agreements signed between 1662 to 1668, driven by changes in the European balance of power. These included the weakening of the relationship between France and the [[Dutch Republic]], allies in the 1568 to 1648 [[Eighty Years War]], and Spain's eclipse by [[Kingdom of France|France]] under [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]].{{sfn|Israel|1990|pp=197-198}}\n\nBy the middle of the 17th century, the [[Spanish Empire]] remained a huge global confederation but needed peace after a century of continuous warfare. The 1635 to 1659 [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u201359)|Franco-Spanish War]] concluded with the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]]; the [[Anglo-Spanish War (1654\u20131660)|1654 to 1660 war]] with the [[Commonwealth of England]] was suspended after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration of Charles II]] in 1660.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|p=50}}\n\nSpain now focused on ending the long-running [[Portuguese Restoration War]]; in [[Treaty of Brussels (1656)|1656]], [[Philip IV of Spain|Philip IV]] agreed to help [[Charles II of England|Charles]] regain his throne, in return for assistance against Portugal. However, in [[Marriage Treaty|May 1661]], Charles agreed to marry [[Catherine of Braganza]] and provide Portugal [[English expedition to Portugal (1662\u20131668)|military support]].{{sfn|Belcher|1975|pp=70-71}}\n\nThis was the result of various factors, one being Philip's insistence on the return of [[Jamaica]], captured in 1656, and [[Siege of Dunkirk (1658)|Dunkirk]], captured in 1658; previously part of the [[Spanish Netherlands]], Charles sold it to France in 1662. Relinquishing Jamaica was viewed with great hostility in England, where [[Parliament of England|Parliament]] voted to annex it in September 1660. English merchants gained access to Portuguese markets in [[Colonial Brazil|Brazil]], Africa and the Far East; the acquisition of [[English Tangier|Tangier]] and [[Bombay]] provided bases in the [[Mediterranean]] and on the [[Surat]] coast. This made it too attractive to refuse but impacted Anglo-Spanish relations.{{sfn|Belcher|1975|pp=72-73}}\n\n==Negotiations==\n[[File:Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|[[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Fanshawe]], English ambassador in [[Lisbon]] (1662-1666) and [[Madrid]], 1664 to 1666; his negotiations were the basis of the 1667 treaty]]\n[[Sir Richard Fanshawe, 1st Baronet|Sir Richard Fanshawe]], English [[List of ambassadors of the Kingdom of England to Portugal|ambassador in Portugal]] from 1662 to 1666, was also appointed [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Spain|ambassador to Spain]] in 1664. He was instructed to agree a treaty of commerce, obtain reparations for losses and confirm possession of territories captured from 1654 to 1660, primarily [[Jamaica]].{{sfn|Riley|2014|p=58}}\n\nIn 1663, Philip launched a major military offensive against Portugal and refused to negotiate while England was assisting 'rebels'.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|p=94}} Talks opened in 1664 when the offensive failed, halted when the [[Second Anglo-Dutch War]] began in March 1665, then restarted following Spanish defeat at the [[Battle of Montes Claros]] in June.{{sfn|Riley|2014|pp=122-123}} Philip died in September, leaving his three year old son [[Charles II of Spain|Charles II]] as king, and his wife [[Mariana of Austria]] as regent.{{sfn|Cowans|2003|pp=26\u201327}}\n[[File:El cardenal Juan Everardo Nithard.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Juan Everardo Nithard|Juan Nithard]], Spanish chief minister]]\nEnding the war with Portugal was a priority for the new Spanish government and [[Juan Everardo Nithard|Juan Nithard]] made an Anglo-Spanish treaty dependent on English help in achieving this. However, Louis encouraged Portugal to insist on harsh terms, seeking to prevent Spain reinforcing the Spanish Netherlands.{{sfn|Geyl|1936|pp=311-312}}\n\nIn December, Fanshawe finalised terms with [[Gaspar de Bracamonte, 3rd Count of Pe\u00f1aranda|Count Pe\u00f1aranda]], a member of the Spanish Regency Council, using the 1630 Treaty of Madrid as a base. They were unaware of discussions in London between the Spanish ambassador, Count Molina, the [[James II of England|Duke of York]] and [[Henry Bennet, 1st Earl of Arlington|Arlington]]. Charles refused to ratify Fanshawe's version, claiming he had exceeded instructions and replaced him with [[Edward Montagu, 1st Earl of Sandwich|Lord Sandwich]]. Fanshawe died in June 1666, shortly before returning home.{{sfn|Lockey|2016|p=260}}\n\nIn March 1667, France and Portugal signed the [[Treaty of Lisbon (1667)|Treaty of Lisbon]], a ten year offensive and defensive alliance against Spain; on 24 May, French troops entered the Spanish Netherlands in the [[War of Devolution]]. Facing the prospect of another ten years of war with Portugal and the loss of their provinces to France, Spain now quickly came to terms.{{sfn|Feiling|2013|pp=232-234}}\n\n==Terms==\nThe prominence of commercial issues in 17th and 18th century diplomacy derived from the economic theory of [[Mercantilism]], which viewed global trade as finite. Increasing your share meant taking it from others, so states protected their own using [[tariff]]s or import bans, while attacking the colonies or ships of others.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rothbard|first1=Murray|title=Mercantilism as the Economic Side of Absolutism|url=https://mises.org/library/mercantilism-economic-side-absolutism|website=Mises.org|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> English complaints related to two areas; exclusion from markets within the [[Spanish Empire]], and restrictions on direct trade between mainland Spain and England.{{sfn|McLachlan|1934|p=299}}\n\nThe 1630 treaty was annulled and on 23 May 1667, England and Spain signed two new treaties; a commercial deal and an agreement by England to mediate a truce between Portugal and Spain.{{sfn|Fisher, Savelle|1967|pp=66-70}} In a separate article, each party undertook not to assist enemies of the other; England would withdraw its Portuguese expeditionary force, while Spain remained neutral in the Anglo-Dutch war.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|pp=96-98}}\n[[File:Potassium nitrate.jpg|thumb|left|upright|180px|[[Saltpetre]]; used in [[gunpowder]], it was hugely profitable for the [[East India Company]], a major beneficiary of the treaty]]\nThe commercial treaty consisted of forty separate articles, the most important being '''Article Seven''', part of Fanshawe's draft but omitted from the original terms.{{sfn|Davenport, Paullin|1917|pp=96-98}} English merchants were given equal status with the Dutch and granted the right to import goods tax free into European Spain.{{sfn|Andrien, Kuethe|2014|pp=50-52}} '''Articles Seven, Eight, Eleven and Twelve''' went further than this, by allowing [[Thirteen Colonies|English colonies in North America]] and the [[East India Company]] to ship goods direct to Spanish ports.{{sfn|McLachlan|1934|p=299}}\n\nBy granting English merchants trading rights within Spanish America, the treaty accepted England's presence in the Caribbean and occupation of Jamaica, although this was not formally recognised until 1670. '''Article Ten''' broadly exempted English ships and warehouses in Spanish ports from customs inspections, disputes being referred to a local judge, nominated by the English and confirmed by Madrid.{{sfn|Andrien, Kuethe|2014|p=50}}\n\n'''Articles Fourteen through Seventeen''' allowed English ships access to ports throughout the Spanish Empire, a significant concession since it greatly increased their operating range.{{sfn|McLachlan|1934|p=299}} '''Article Thirty-Eight''' made English merchants equivalent to the Dutch and French by awarding them [[most favoured nation]] status; its implementation was resisted by Spanish merchants and had to be re-iterated in the [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|1670 Treaty]].{{sfn|Stein, Stein|2000|p=63}} \n\nThese concessions were the first step in challenging Dutch economic supremacy outside Europe and thus of greater significance than often appreciated; they remained in place until the outbreak of the [[War of the Spanish Succession]] in 1701.{{sfn|Lodge|1932|p=3}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:An English Merchant Ship in a Mediterranean Harbour in a Light Breeze with Many Other Vessels RMG BHC0890.tiff|thumb|right|200px|English ship in harbour, ca 1680; the treaty allowed access to ports throughout the Spanish Empire ]]\nEconomic historian Guillermo P\u00e9rez Sarri\u00f3n claims the 1667 treaty demonstrates 'England's absolute dominance of Anglo-Spanish trade'.{{sfn|Sarrion|2016|p=57}} One London merchant later described it as \u2018the best flower in our garden'; English goods were imported through [[Cadiz]], then sold locally or re-exported to the colonies, Spanish dye and wool going the other way.{{sfn|Mclachlan|1940|p=6}}\n\nFranco-Spanish trade primarily consisted of bulk imports like grain and timber, which were easily regulated by local authorities. English trade was predominantly maritime, within the vast Spanish Empire, and much harder to control; the treaty effectively permitted ships captains to decide what goods were listed on their [[Manifest (transportation)|manifest]] as 'English'.{{sfn| Sarrion|2016|p=58}} This allowed English merchants to evade customs duties, demand from Spanish colonists creating a large and extremely profitable [[black market]].{{sfn|Richmond|1920|p=2}}\n\nIn September, [[Afonso VI of Portugal]] was deposed in a coup led by his brother [[Peter II of Portugal|Pedro]]; the previous treaty with France was annulled and with England as mediator, Spain and Portugal signed the [[Treaty of Lisbon (1668)|Treaty of Lisbon]] on 13 February 1668.{{sfn|Newitt|2004|p=228}} Relieved of this burden and backed by the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]], Spain ended the War of Devolution with France by agreeing the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1668)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]] on 5 May.{{sfn|Davenport, Paulin|1917|p=144}}\n\nThe question of Spanish possessions in the [[West Indies]] captured by England in 1654 to 1660 was later settled in the [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|1670 Treaty of Madrid]].{{sfn|Fisher, Savelle|1967|pp=66-70}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Andrien|first1=Kenneth J|last2=Kuethe|first2=Allan J|title=The Spanish Atlantic World in the Eighteenth Century: War and the Bourbon Reforms, 1713\u20131796|date=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9781107043572|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Belcher |first1=Gerald |title=Spain and the Anglo-Portuguese Alliance of 1661: A Reassessment of Charles II's Foreign Policy at the Restoration |journal=British Studies |date=1975 |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=67\u201388 |doi=10.1086/385679 |jstor=175239 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cowans|first1=Jon|title=Modern Spain: A Documentary History|year=2003|publisher=U. of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-1846-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Davenport|editor1-first=Frances Gardiner|editor2-last=Paullin|editor2-first=Charles Oscar|title=European Treaties Bearing on the History of the United States and Its Dependencies, Vol. 2: 1650-1697|date=1917|publisher=Forgotten Books|isbn=978-0483158924|edition=2018|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Feiling|first1=Keith|title=British Foreign Policy 1660-1972|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136241543|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Fisher|first1=Margaret Anne|last2=Savelle|first2=Max|title=The origins of American diplomacy: the international history of Angloamerica, 1492-1763 American diplomatic history series Authors|date=1967|publisher=Macmillan|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Xxd2AAAAMAAJ&dq=|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Geyl |first1=P |title=Johan de Witt, Grand Pensionary of Holland, 1653\u201372 |journal=History |date=1936 |volume=20 |issue=80 |pages=303\u2013319 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-229X.1936.tb00103.x |jstor=24401084 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book|last1=Israel|first1=Jonathan|title=Dutch Primacy in World Trade, 1585\u20131740|date=1989|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0198211396|ref=harv|edition=1990}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Lockey|first1=Brian C|title=Early Modern Catholics, Royalists, and Cosmopolitans: English Transnationalism and the Christian Commonwealth Transculturalisms, 1400-1700|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317147107|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Lodge |first1=Richard |title=Presidential Address: Sir Benjamin Keene, K.B.: A Study in Anglo-Spanish Relations in the Earlier Part of the Eighteenth Century|journal=Transactions of the Royal Historical Society |date=1932 |volume=15 |pages=1\u201343 |ref=harv |doi=10.2307/3678642|jstor=3678642 }}